Media notes: Immature Northern Shrike at McAllister County Park in the Village of Belle Terre, Suffolk County, NY (November 9, 2015)
Observation Details: *Uncommon on LI in late fall/winter in appropriate habitat. Quite early for Northern. Flushed up out of dense shrubs while trying to relocate the Western Kingbird. Quite a surprise. Large, upright Lanius with longer, hooked bill. Immature bird with weak narrow mask, not extending above eye (also faint eye ring). Mostly grayish/brown overall with black wings and white inner primary patch. Crisp horizontal vermiculation extending throughout underparts. Also seen well in flight while the bird continued to hunt the area favoring bare deciduous trees and scattered red cedar. Seen hovering (kestrel-like) and diving into patches of shrubs, targeting prey. Also heard vocalizing a number of times ("nasaly" call notes). Documentation photos attached to this report.

I covered about five miles on foot and encountered three individual northern shrikes in seperate areas. One is a continuing bird previously photographed directly north on the visitors center, the second is on the East side of the 'Drovers' unit(can provide coordinates), and the third is in the middle of the Sandstone unit (can provide coordinates). Some photos taken of the two new birds, I'll drive over and try for photos of the continuing bird since it was seen at a distance. All the were large lanky pale shrikes with narrow masks that didn't cover the eye, a long deeply hooked two toned bill, horizontal barring on the chests. This brings the total for barton county to five present NSHRs.  I can give directions for all these birds if anyone wants to chase but either the one just north of the visitors center or the one on the west side of Shawnee trail are by far the most easily accessible of the 5 currently in Barton county.

The third day in a row this bird has been in the park. Probably the most cooperative Northern Shrike I have ever encountered. Additionally, for a period of approximately 35 minutes this morning between approximately 8:15 and 8:50 AM the bird was very vocal allowing me to obtain several recordings.

Locality: Creve Coeur Lake Memorial Park--Little Creve Coeur
Observation Details: From 38°42′37″ N  90°30′39″ W on the trail.  Bird flew into my FOV from the N and stopped to perch right in front of me, up in a tree, at a range of about 25 yards in excellent light.  My very first thought with eyes-only was cuckoo but, no, it was clearly a shrike with narrow mask, not covering the eye, and stout, not stubby, distinctly hooked bill—all well seen in the bins.  Also, largeish-looking; white on the forehead above the bill; dingy throat; variable amounts of white all around the eye forming a complete eyering; extensively barred underparts; small white patch at base of primaries really just a combination of white streaks.  Bird quickly flew away to the S.

Recordist: Nate Adams and Joey Danielsen Adams
Observation Details: Saw it suddenly appear in pursuit of a Tree Sparrow. It did not catch the Tree Sparrow and sat in a tree overlooking our feeders for about 15 minutes. No birds appeared and the Northern Shrike gave up and flew to a tree in the neighbor's yard where we did not have a good view of it.  No birds at our feeders or anywhere that we could see in our yard for over an hour after the Northern Shrike left. It was so quiet. Not even any Chickadees chirping, which is usually pretty constant in our yard. Very exciting for us, though -- we have never seen a Northern Shrike and one came right to our yard!

I assume this is the same individual that was first reported  by Hommert and Dean on Jan 15, 2020 at Bradford. It has been reported by about 5 additional birders on 15 Jan, then by Freibohle on 20 Jan, Decker and Pelc on 27 Jan, Bieksza on Jan 29, Johnson again on 10 March and myself on 17 March. This bird has been eluding many observers but it is still present. One NSHR lingered into late April, so stop by the dump pile in the early to mid-morning and give it a chance to show up. This bird is larger than a Loggerhead Shrike, narrower black mask, long heavy beak with a distinct hook at end of bill. The base of the lower mandible has a white patch. This is an adult bird with no brown of the immature shrike and has a strongly gray wavy thin lines on a lighter gray underside.The upper-parts are paler compared to the medium blue-gray upper-parts of a Loggerhead Shrike. This individual slowly bobbed its tail as I watched it perched on the top weeds above the dump pile.There is a white crescent over the eye and noticeably white over the bill. There is a slight hint of an eye ring at the lower edge of the eye.

Locality: Anderson Rd. (Woodbury-Southbury Rod and Gun Club Farm)
Observation Details: Continuing bird, being reported for the last week or so.  My first of this species in the state.  I found this bird (not until about 20 minutes after I arrives) about halfway between the little pond with the "W" sign and the red barn up the hill that it was reported behind.  It was near the road in a thicket.  It flew towards the house and feeders behind the pond.  It then flew back towards me, landing in the brambles just behind my parked car, at the "W" sign.  I got real good photos but a passing box truck spooked it.  It disappeared for a while but was seen again making roughly the same circuit about an hour later.  I have a feeling this bird spends more time hunting songbirds in the thickets than the treetops, so persistence will pay off.

It was a very quiet Grey Cup celebration here, but I did some cleaning downstairs anyway! ;)  While earning those "brownie" points in anticipation of next week's CBCs, Sandra yelled “Get up here - what’s this bird??!!”  I quickly made it upstairs in time to see THIS bad boy sitting on the pergola.   While apparently the NSHR had no success trying to grab an afternoon snack, it was still VERY cool to see this species perched on our pergola from only a few metres away.   I’m guessing this is the possibly the same first-year bird that was here back on Nov. 1.  I managed a few snaps  with our little Canon SX720 HS before it flew off to the west.
It only allowed me to take a  quick picture of it. Beautiful bird.

**Rare, a complete surprise. Flew right past Ant and I and perched on a tree south of the trail just west of the bathrooms. Super crisp adult with a bold facial mask and dark contrasting black and white on the wings, lending itself to a brief misidentification of loggerhead shrike, but the facial mask was sufficiently narrow for a quick revision. Subsequently seen with Isaac Grant and company, who were nearby when Ant and I sent out the alert. Quite active, flying back and forth from tree to tree and landing on a methane vent before strongly flying east and dropping into vegetation and out of view. Originally encountered here (40.5872274, -74.1858331); last seen dropping down low somewhere around the crossroad and locked gate here (40.5875334, -74.1846070)

One of the most annoying things is going after a special bird and just not finding it! The location of the farm is not where I saw the bird at all. After walking around the whole area I got back into my car and drove back to where I had come in.  I found the bird thanks to David Medd’s location. It is currently the more accurate spot for spotting the shrike. (For sure as of the last few days.) I originally spotted the bird at about 41.4477324, -73.8677037. It was on a small tree about 8 feet tall just behind, a couple piles of wood chips, covered in tarp. When I stepped out of my car, I scared it into the shrubs, lower down, making it very difficult to see and then I lost it entirely. Good luck to anyone who tries to find it! Photos coming!   41.4477324, -73.8677037

Media notes: Stewart Fletcher, Photographer.  NSHR imm Brown 1st-WtrAfter 2 pellets discharged - CROP no longer distended!  Quickly leaves perch!
Observation Details: 12:52 to 13:13 -  1st heard (buzzy, harsh breezeek note followed by a pause and repeated 2 more times); locate/visual 1 immature BROWN 1st WINTER (see The Sibley Guide to Birds, pg 341) NSHR (ID species in part by its pinkish base of lower mandible) perched in top of hardwood tree and remaining in place for a lengthy time --- usual shrike behavior is actively foraging.  BEHAVIOR:  Stays put (unlike a shrike that is a very active forager) on perch - turns out it is in wait mode.  Opens mouth wide 4xs - notice an enlargement in its CROP (photograph 2) after ~3rd open-mouth series, which pushes two pellets into crop from digestive tract; next TWO pellets are disgorged/discharged from mouth to the ground one-after-the-other - 1st pellet is small (documented by a lesser quality photo and also witnessed with binoculars) and 2nd pellet is large (photographs 3 and 4).  Stewart Fletcher, Photographer

Only the third time I've ever seen this species. Unfortunately, it was found by our farm manager in the chicken coop in the morning. It appears that the shrike killed a pigeon and was then attacked by the chickens. By the time I got there, it had a broken leg and two badly injured wings. Given the condition of the roads, all we could do was put it in a warm greenhouse. I tried to offer it fresh pork, which it refused. It managed to somehow catch and kill a vole, but died several hours later.

Continuing immature shrike reported yesterday in the hedgerow of a large farm field on the corner of Varga and Wormwood Hill Rd.  The farm is adjacent to Leander Pond and across the street from Knowlton Pond.  Brownish barring on breast, black mask clearly visible but not bold, hooked bill.  In typical behavior of shrikes, it appears to be stalking tree sparrows and house finches, and had a meal of something while we watched it.  It then flew up to perch at the top of a tall sapling which overlooks the hedgerow directly in front of us allowing for awesome looks and a photo op.

Media notes: Immature Northern Shrike at McAllister County Park in the Village of Belle Terre, Suffolk County, NY (November 9, 2015)
Observation Details: *Uncommon on LI in late fall/winter in appropriate habitat. Quite early for Northern. Flushed up out of dense shrubs while trying to relocate the Western Kingbird. Quite a surprise. Large, upright Lanius with longer, hooked bill. Immature bird with weak narrow mask, not extending above eye (also faint eye ring). Mostly grayish/brown overall with black wings and white inner primary patch. Crisp horizontal vermiculation extending throughout underparts. Also seen well in flight while the bird continued to hunt the area favoring bare deciduous trees and scattered red cedar. Seen hovering (kestrel-like) and diving into patches of shrubs, targeting prey. Also heard vocalizing a number of times ("nasaly" call notes). Documentation photos attached to this report.

***Lincoln County Lifer***.  Third time this year was a charm.  Observed just south of waterfowl HQ, in biggest tree on right side of road where tree line crosses road.  I actually drove right past, underneath this bird.  Only noticed it b/c I was watching Northern Flickers that flew by and landed in a tree behind me.  Just so happens, the shrike was perched in center near top of same tree, well hidden.   Sightings in this general area go all the way back to 2018; so, possibly a returning bird since 2018 (although there are no eBird reports in 2022.  First reported this winter 2 Jan by Mark Schuver.    Notes: - Thin black mask that does not go over top of bill. - Strongly hooked, thinner bill (than Loggerhead). - White touches top of eye, and white over top of bill.

I found what appears to be an immature Northern Shrike perched high atop a large cottonwood tree along the NE perimeter of the public access area, near the parking lot.  Both Sam Hough and I were able to get photos of the bird.  After reviewing the photos at home and consulting a number of books, I am convinced this is an immature Northern Shrike rather than an immature Loggerhead Shrike.  Characteristics that support this conclusion are:  * At this time of the year, an immature Loggerhead Shrike should have fairly close to adult plumage; this bird has retained some of its juvenile characteristics, and the plumage is quite different than that of an adult.  * Brown head with narrow mask that does not extend above the middle of the eyes; mask thinner in front of the eyes; white eye ring fairly easily seen.  * Bill not as long as what you would see in an adult; extensive pale area at base of lower mandible.  * Back has no barring and has a light brown tint.  * Very obvious light brown tint scaling on breast, belly and flanks (not barring like a juvenile Loggerhead Shrike).

Continuing shrike found by Todd Ramsden. Showed up in middle of previously reported open area around 0958 after not being detected during my first walk around the perimeter of the area, then stayed in view for approximately the next hour before disappearing again. Initially seen perched on top of a tree here (39.9025164, -122.0727698), then flew to a couple trees nearby during my visit.   Large shrike - seemed larger than LOSH, though hard to judge without side-by-side comparison; substantial dark bill with pronounced hook to upper mandible, paler towards base; white over top of base of bill; weaker black mask than LOSH - more prominent behind the eye (a little bit wider than one eye width and about as long as two eye widths) than in front of it, and with white completely surrounding the eye, almost like spectacles; black eye; gray from crown to rump; rump whitish; upper tail black; whitish/very pale underparts with warm wash and fine barring from breast to belly that appeared maroon or brownish in my scope; black wings with small white wing patch and white tips to (secondaries/tertials?) and very thin pale tips to primaries; whitish utcs; black legs; underside of tail appeared mostly white due to white (tail spots?), though I never saw the tail spread well. [Notes taken before looking at my photos or field guide.]  After spending some time perched at the top of a tree, the shrike laddered down through the branches and then dove down into some nearby low bushes. It quickly maneuvered through them before flying back up to the tree holding what appeared to be a very downy and gray bird chick in its bill. After impaling the presumed chick on one of the branches, it proceeded to rip it up and eat the whole thing. Shortly after this, it started vocalizing spontaneously for the first time during my observation. I believe I heard and recorded at least three different types of vocalizations, which was extremely cool. It then spent the remainder of my observation generally preening, cleaning its bill against branches and surveying its realm before making a short flight and then disappearing.  All in all, I'm not sure if I've had a more prolonged and satisfying experience with a single bird in California since I started birding. Stoked the gamble of driving all the way up here for this bird paid off.  Photos. Audio. Video.

The farm is adjacent to Leander Pond and across the street from Knowlton Pond.  Brownish barring on breast, black mask clearly visible but not bold, hooked bill. It then flew up to perch at the top of a tall sapling which overlooks the hedgerow directly in front of us allowing for awesome looks and a photo op.

Observation Details: Saw it suddenly appear in pursuit of a Tree Sparrow. It did not catch the Tree Sparrow and sat in a tree overlooking our feeders for about 15 minutes. No birds appeared and the Northern Shrike gave up and flew to a tree in the neighbor's yard where we did not have a good view of it.  No birds at our feeders or anywhere that we could see in our yard for over an hour after the Northern Shrike left. It was so quiet. Not even any Chickadees chirping, which is usually pretty constant in our yard. Very exciting for us, though -- we have never seen a Northern Shrike and one came right to our yard!

Two birds observed sporadically for over an hour. Would perch for several minutes from time to time but more usually flitting from branch to branch at height of 5-10m. Occasionally highly vocal. Calls recorded as mew-like, complaining, frequent short bursts of two note and two syllable "zhee - zhouuu". Sounded like gulls fighting but less harsh and less robust. Possibly younger bird harassing older bird for food. Both birds seen together, one at one point with feathers in bill suggesting recent kill or feed.   Thick bold black eyestripe on soft grey face, width of eye only, slightly curved downwards before nape; cheeks whiter than pale grey breast, which was crossed with faint (but clear) slightly scalloped darker bars. Forward-leaning pose (although winds were brisk). Black primaries and secondaries, darker plain grey back. Longish tail edged white. Both birds appeared white rather than brown.

See photos.  This bird had a black mask that narrowed significantly as it reached the eye and met the bill, but the mask did not cover the top of the bill, as it would if this bird had been a Loggerhead Shrike.  A Loggerhead would have had a thicker mask and it would have spread more extensively over the eye and bill.  Notice in the photos that this bird also had the white markings around the eye distinctive in Northern, the thick white stripe bordering the top of the mask. This adult bird also showed the barring that is characteristic of a Northern adult, but only found on Loggerheads as immatures.  One last detail that we felt made this a Northern - the bill had a pale base, which would usually have be all black on a Loggerhead.  For anyone looking for this bird, we found her/him in the first parking lot of the River Slough Tract (the parking lot at the very beginning of the tract) on top of a short bush being chased by a Red-bellied Woodpecker.  She then flew across the road atop other small bushes adjacent the road, then to the phone wire. We watched as she hunted in the part of the tract that is still open to the public, but at one point she flew deep into the area only accessible to hunters right now.

Medium sized passerine - light gray above with lighter underside, black wings and mask, hooked bill.  Photos.  This was a cool sighting.  After spotting the shrike out in a distant tree, I sat down and watched it for awhile and eventually was rewarded to see it fly to a tree near me, then dive to the ground and come up with a mouse/small rodent.  It clung to the unfortunate victim with one, then both feet, much like a raptor with its prey - then flew with it deep into the branches of another tree further from me where it tore into the rodent, eating it immediately, and not caching it.

Awesome find by Keith Klein on 11/24 and again 12/02.  As we were beginning our search the bird vocalized and we all frantically starting scanning the area. Benjamin Bolduc spotted the bird in the distance perched on top of high trees.  It flew down into the field where we were standing (same area as Keith described). It continued for some time in the same general vicinity being pursued/pursuing a few Northern Mockingbirds. Muddy grey upperparts and pale grey streaked underparts. Black mask and heavy bill with hook on end. Faint wing bars. Looks to be an immature bird. Photos.

I found what appears to be an immature Northern Shrike perched high atop a large cottonwood tree along the NE perimeter of the public access area, near the parking lot.  Both Sam Hough and I were able to get photos of the bird.  After reviewing the photos at home and consulting a number of books, I am convinced this is an immature Northern Shrike rather than an immature Loggerhead Shrike.  Characteristics that support this conclusion are:  * At this time of the year, an immature Loggerhead Shrike should have fairly close to adult plumage; this bird has retained some of its juvenile characteristics, and the plumage is quite different than that of an adult.  * Brown head with narrow mask that does not extend above the middle of the eyes; mask thinner in front of the eyes; white eye ring fairly easily seen.  * Bill not as long as what you would see in an adult; extensive pale area at base of lower mandible.  * Back has no barring and has a light brown tint.  * Very obvious light brown tint scaling on breast, belly and flanks (not barring like a juvenile Loggerhead Shrike).

Continuing shrike found by Todd Ramsden. Showed up in middle of previously reported open area around 0958 after not being detected during my first walk around the perimeter of the area, then stayed in view for approximately the next hour before disappearing again. Initially seen perched on top of a tree here (39.9025164, -122.0727698), then flew to a couple trees nearby during my visit.   Large shrike - seemed larger than LOSH, though hard to judge without side-by-side comparison; substantial dark bill with pronounced hook to upper mandible, paler towards base; white over top of base of bill; weaker black mask than LOSH - more prominent behind the eye (a little bit wider than one eye width and about as long as two eye widths) than in front of it, and with white completely surrounding the eye, almost like spectacles; black eye; gray from crown to rump; rump whitish; upper tail black; whitish/very pale underparts with warm wash and fine barring from breast to belly that appeared maroon or brownish in my scope; black wings with small white wing patch and white tips to (secondaries/tertials?) and very thin pale tips to primaries; whitish utcs; black legs; underside of tail appeared mostly white due to white (tail spots?), though I never saw the tail spread well. [Notes taken before looking at my photos or field guide.]  After spending some time perched at the top of a tree, the shrike laddered down through the branches and then dove down into some nearby low bushes. It quickly maneuvered through them before flying back up to the tree holding what appeared to be a very downy and gray bird chick in its bill. After impaling the presumed chick on one of the branches, it proceeded to rip it up and eat the whole thing. Shortly after this, it started vocalizing spontaneously for the first time during my observation. I believe I heard and recorded at least three different types of vocalizations, which was extremely cool. It then spent the remainder of my observation generally preening, cleaning its bill against branches and surveying its realm before making a short flight and then disappearing.  All in all, I'm not sure if I've had a more prolonged and satisfying experience with a single bird in California since I started birding. Stoked the gamble of driving all the way up here for this bird paid off.  Photos. Audio. Video.

Locality: Walden Ponds Wildlife Habitat--Walden & Sawhill Ponds all together

Media notes: Stewart Fletcher, Photographer;  NSHR immature Brown 1st-WTR.  Opens mouth wide 4xs - CROP enlargement visible.
Observation Details: 12:52 to 13:13 -  1st heard (buzzy, harsh breezeek note followed by a pause and repeated 2 more times); locate/visual 1 immature BROWN 1st WINTER (see The Sibley Guide to Birds, pg 341) NSHR (ID species in part by its pinkish base of lower mandible) perched in top of hardwood tree and remaining in place for a lengthy time --- usual shrike behavior is actively foraging.  BEHAVIOR:  Stays put (unlike a shrike that is a very active forager) on perch - turns out it is in wait mode.  Opens mouth wide 4xs - notice an enlargement in its CROP (photograph 2) after ~3rd open-mouth series, which pushes two pellets into crop from digestive tract; next TWO pellets are disgorged/discharged from mouth to the ground one-after-the-other - 1st pellet is small (documented by a lesser quality photo and also witnessed with binoculars) and 2nd pellet is large (photographs 3 and 4).  Stewart Fletcher, Photographer

The third day in a row this bird has been in the park. Probably the most cooperative Northern Shrike I have ever encountered. Although it doesn't allow close approach, it tolerates my presence at a discreet distance and today remained visible and active in the area during the entirety of my morning stay. Additionally, for a period of approximately 35 minutes this morning between approximately 8:15 and 8:50 AM the bird was very vocal allowing me to obtain several recordings.

I assume this is the same individual that was first reported  by Hommert and Dean on Jan 15, 2020 at Bradford. It has been reported by about 5 additional birders on 15 Jan, then by Freibohle on 20 Jan, Decker and Pelc on 27 Jan, Bieksza on Jan 29, Johnson again on 10 March and myself on 17 March. This bird has been eluding many observers but it is still present. One NSHR lingered into late April, so stop by the dump pile in the early to mid-morning and give it a chance to show up. This bird is larger than a Loggerhead Shrike, narrower black mask, long heavy beak with a distinct hook at end of bill. The base of the lower mandible has a white patch. This is an adult bird with no brown of the immature shrike and has a strongly gray wavy thin lines on a lighter gray underside.The upper-parts are paler compared to the medium blue-gray upper-parts of a Loggerhead Shrike. This individual slowly bobbed its tail as I watched it perched on the top weeds above the dump pile.There is a white crescent over the eye and noticeably white over the bill. There is a slight hint of an eye ring at the lower edge of the eye.

I have an excellent photo for confirmation; see https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.2900940412101.148147.1518159192&type=1#!/photo.php?fbid=2900944732209&set=a.2900940412101.148147.1518159192&type=1&theater

Locality: Rocky Point Bird Observatory (no public access)
Rancho Tehama Road, ca. ¼ km W of Paskenta Road
Observation Details: This was a well-marked bird, yet it lacked bright coloration.  The face pattern was somewhat more complex but also weaker than that of a Loggerhead Shrike.  The mask was conspicuously narrow and essentially restricted to an elongate region of dull, blackish that extended from just behind the eye across the auriculars, though there was at least some darker coloration extending under the eye and into the lores.  Contrasting with the dark mask was the rich buff-forehead that connected with a buffy supraloral stripe and complete eyering.  I noted no blackish coloration in front of or above the eye, so the upper edge of the mask extended from the eyering back along the upper edge of the auriculars before curving around their rear terminus and then continuing back forward along the lower edge of the auriculars and less conspicuously the moustachial region.  The crown, nape, and back and sides of the neck were uniformly medium-brown with a gray cast, with the brown of the sides of the neck curving around to demarcate the rear terminus of the auriculars and then extend down to the sides of the breast.  The back and scapulars were similarly colored, but with the distal scapulars having a relatively narrow and diffuse crescent of pale-buff.  The closed wings appeared to be entirely dull black apart from narrow tips of white to the secondaries just above the slightly lighter and more brownish wingtip.  In fact, I had a hard time distinguishing the coverts and remiges in the closed wing.  It was only when the bird spread its wing to preen that I noted a narrow band of creamy-buff along the bases of primaries that appeared uniformly paler and more brownish than the rest of the wing.  The upper part of the rump was the same color as the back, but the grayish-brown blended to creamy-buff on the lower rump and possibly also the uppertail coverts.  The upperside of the closed tail was blackish much like the wings, but when the tail was spread I noted a whitish margin even when seen from above.  When seen from below, the outer rectrices were extensively white, at least along their outer edges, but when the bird spread its tail I noted that the white curved around the outer edges distally, though I did not think it reached the central feathers.  Contrasting with the darker upperparts, the underparts were generally light gray, though with the malar and submoustachial regions buffy, and a brownish wash to the sides of the breast and the rear flanks.  Also apparent across the breast, sides, belly, and flanks was dusky barring that was relatively narrow, well-defined, and with a wavy appearance.  The undertail coverts were more purely whitish and apparently unmarked, but I am less sure about both the color and pattern on the throat.  The bill was generally blackish but with the basal half or so of the lower mandible either pinkish or fleshy.  The eyes were dark, but I was unable to see any color.  What I was able to see of the legs and feet was black.

I saw a Shrike in a dead snag in the reclaimed area where raptors and the Shrike (when they are here) often sit.    After I took some photos and looked at them on my camera I discovered that an American Kestrel had replaced the Shrike on top of the snag.  That set off a round of furious calling by the Shrike as it repeatedly dove on the Kestrel.  In the middle of this a second Shrike showed up and joined the fray, although it was not clear which side it was on.  Later I saw a Shrike on the other side of the river, which I am assuming was one of the two previously seen.

Locality: Priest Butte Rd (7 Ln NW), Fairfield
Hoback and Beattie St Area Neighborhoods
Observation Details: Hatch-year bird first seen at 1141 perched in the top of a leafless Prunus virginiana clump within 30 m of a house, on the NW flank of Sugarloaf Hill, with sloping grassland on 2 sides and residential houses interspersed with trees and gardens on the other sides. Brownish with faint mask and distinct barring underneath and a small pale patch at the base of the primaries. At the time I thought the appearance differed from the bird seen on 29 Oct about 500 m SSW, but comparison of photos reveals a very similar aspect. Thus, it seems quite likely that this is the same individual. Observed from 10 to 15 meters away until 1146, when it flew relatively directly about 40 m to the top of a cottonwood, also at the neighborhood edge. It remained there 1 or 2 minutes, then flew ca NW. Flight was direct and surprisingly (to me) fast with quick series of wingbeats punctuated by notable, short pauses; little undulation in flight. Not seen again during the rest of the count.

Continuing immature shrike reported yesterday in the hedgerow of a large farm field on the corner of Varga and Wormwood Hill Rd.  The farm is adjacent to Leander Pond and across the street from Knowlton Pond.  Brownish barring on breast, black mask clearly visible but not bold, hooked bill.  In typical behavior of shrikes, it appears to be stalking tree sparrows and house finches, and had a meal of something while we watched it.  It then flew up to perch at the top of a tall sapling which overlooks the hedgerow directly in front of us allowing for awesome looks and a photo op.

Media notes: The late afternoon sun popped out after the rain stopped and this stunning bird turned almost a creamy colour.
Observation Details: VERY excited to see this bird fly in this afternoon!! He flew in over the feeding area where the Juncos and other sparrows were--fast as could be!! Many sparrows jumped down into the daisy foliage and we wondered why--THEN we knew!! Didn't take any--rather, landed on an Arbutus Limb. Then, it flew onto our curved sign log--then to two other logs, always watching the feeding area up by the house. This gave us lots of opportunity to view it--a beautiful bird for sure!! Colours changed with the lighting--it had been raining and it's colours were quite grey--the late afternoon sun popped out, low in the sky and it's appearance turned a creamy colour.

Observation Details: Continuing bird, being reported for the last week or so.  My first of this species in the state.  I found this bird (not until about 20 minutes after I arrives) about halfway between the little pond with the "W" sign and the red barn up the hill that it was reported behind.  It was near the road in a thicket.  It flew towards the house and feeders behind the pond.  It then flew back towards me, landing in the brambles just behind my parked car, at the "W" sign.  I got real good photos but a passing box truck spooked it.  It disappeared for a while but was seen again making roughly the same circuit about an hour later.  I have a feeling this bird spends more time hunting songbirds in the thickets than the treetops, so persistence will pay off.

Two birds observed sporadically for over an hour. Would perch for several minutes from time to time but more usually flitting from branch to branch at height of 5-10m. Occasionally highly vocal. Calls recorded as mew-like, complaining, frequent short bursts of two note and two syllable "zhee - zhouuu". Sounded like gulls fighting but less harsh and less robust. Possibly younger bird harassing older bird for food. Both birds seen together, one at one point with feathers in bill suggesting recent kill or feed.   Thick bold black eyestripe on soft grey face, width of eye only, slightly curved downwards before nape; cheeks whiter than pale grey breast, which was crossed with faint (but clear) slightly scalloped darker bars. Forward-leaning pose (although winds were brisk). Black primaries and secondaries, darker plain grey back. Longish tail edged white. Both birds appeared white rather than brown.

Locality: Upper Truckee River--marsh trail and offshore
Observation Details: Apparently continuing from 11/21, which is 2 weeks ago so I'm shocked that it is still here, especially since I haven't seen any other reports of it. First seen sitting on the large tree right next to the big pond, and it always liked to return to that tree when people scared it off. It was very skittish and would fly whenever someone walked past. I got very lucky, since I was actually standing under the tree when it flew up once, and it apparently didn't notice me, so I got great views of it. Appeared to be an adult, classic shrike appearance with long tail, gray body, black mask, and black wings with white patches on them. Closer inspection showed that black mask didn't extend onto the forehead, there was barring on its chest, and it had a larger more down-curved bill than a Loggerhead Shrike. I have many pictures. It was not at the same tree when I walked past going back.

*Very rare in Cape May Co.; found a few minutes earlier by Alan Crawford. Paler backed and smaller headed than LOSH. Relatively narrow mask with eye bulging up; faint grayish in front of eye, and whitish over base of bill. Bill relatively long with obvious bale base to lower mandible, and strong hook at tip. Faint grayish barring/vermiculations on buff-white underparts. White rump. Perched on both high treetops and low shrubs, and went to ground several times, picking up insects (maybe crickets). Several aggressive encounters with Mockingbirds.

Found by Debby Parker 28 Oct. Life bird and on our backyard birdfeeder!  A brown barred shrike with a noticeably long and hooked bill. The brown horizontal barring on the breast was discrete and fine but obvious. Continued through 30 Nov 2002.

Continuing shrike found by Todd Ramsden. Showed up in middle of previously reported open area around 0958 after not being detected during my first walk around the perimeter of the area, then stayed in view for approximately the next hour before disappearing again. Initially seen perched on top of a tree here (39.9025164, -122.0727698), then flew to a couple trees nearby during my visit.   Large shrike - seemed larger than LOSH, though hard to judge without side-by-side comparison; substantial dark bill with pronounced hook to upper mandible, paler towards base; white over top of base of bill; weaker black mask than LOSH - more prominent behind the eye (a little bit wider than one eye width and about as long as two eye widths) than in front of it, and with white completely surrounding the eye, almost like spectacles; black eye; gray from crown to rump; rump whitish; upper tail black; whitish/very pale underparts with warm wash and fine barring from breast to belly that appeared maroon or brownish in my scope; black wings with small white wing patch and white tips to (secondaries/tertials?) and very thin pale tips to primaries; whitish utcs; black legs; underside of tail appeared mostly white due to white (tail spots?), though I never saw the tail spread well. [Notes taken before looking at my photos or field guide.]  After spending some time perched at the top of a tree, the shrike laddered down through the branches and then dove down into some nearby low bushes. It quickly maneuvered through them before flying back up to the tree holding what appeared to be a very downy and gray bird chick in its bill. After impaling the presumed chick on one of the branches, it proceeded to rip it up and eat the whole thing. Shortly after this, it started vocalizing spontaneously for the first time during my observation. I believe I heard and recorded at least three different types of vocalizations, which was extremely cool. It then spent the remainder of my observation generally preening, cleaning its bill against branches and surveying its realm before making a short flight and then disappearing.  All in all, I'm not sure if I've had a more prolonged and satisfying experience with a single bird in California since I started birding. Stoked the gamble of driving all the way up here for this bird paid off.  Photos. Audio. Video.

Observation Details: **yay! probably my 3rd try or so for this species in the state and my first sighting of one in 5 years — one of the longest absences ever for a species on my life list. if you want to see this species in CT, go for this one — it’s being unusually reliable and showy. took me 20 minutes before i heard the distinctive sharp double-note song of this species and immediately afterward saw it in a tree close to the trail here (41.8421078, -72.5660397). recordings and photos. showed up half an hour later for more viewing opportunities.

Continuing birds. At 11:03, I found the juvenile Northern Shrike on the east side of N2780 Rd about 40 yards south of the junction of N2780 and E0480 Rd. The bird was on the top of a small tree right on the road. As previously reported, the bird is brown with white underparts with an indistinct mask and a pale eye arc along the edge of the eye and a long bill with a prominent hook. Photos attached.  Approximately 8 minutes later, I found the subadult gray immature bird on the north side of E0480 on a snag of a tree about 30 yards west of the N2780 and E0480 junction. The immature subadult was grey with a more distinct narrow black eye mask which did not extend above the superior aspect of the eye with white directly above the eye as compared to the Loggerhead Shrike in which the dark eye mask encompasses the eye. I did find two Loggerhead shrikes also with one being on a telephone wire on the west side of N2780 about 60 yards north of the junction. Photos of the juvenile and immature adult Northern Shrikes are attached as are photos of the Loggerhead Shrike.

Locality: Eastern EC County - Karow & Kelly Rds (44.69, -91.059)
Sevenmile Creek--Prickly Pear Land Trust (restricted access)
Observation Details: First observation at 0933. 1 counted on property. 1 individual(s) singing. Adult. First seen at the very beginning of the survey, perched on a metal fencepost SW of the start point. Later seen perched in the Acer negundo N of the stream in reach 4, then flying upstream to another perch after dropping down in the grasses. Next seen perched in the Prunus virginiana row in the SE part of reach 3, where it sang for several minutes. Seemed to imitate several species, including BBMA. Ca 1045 in reach 3, the shrike suddenly appeared and flew in aerial pursuit of 1 ATSP for ca 150 m E along the stream; it had apparently been unsuccessful when last seen perched near there in a dead Alnus incana over a pond. Later, NSHR seen in reach 1, hunting and perching in chokecherry thickets N of the stream. Detections (number 15-minute intervals in which the species was detected): 4 on property.

Observation Details: We investigated the area at BK where the Shrike was located before being informed by Dave Haenni that the area manager would prefer birders stay out of the area until after Jan. 1, 2019, so we won't reveal any more information on his location other than B.K. Leach in general, in order to attempt to honor the wishes of the area manager.  This Northern Shrike had the thin black mask that did not go over the eye and above the bill as it does on a Loggerhead Shrike.  The characteristic fine barring of the adult Northern Shrike was also very evident.  The bill was more elongated-looking and had a more pronounced hook on this bird, as is on a Northern Shrike. A Loggerhead bill would be more short and chunky with a less pronounced hook.  Please see photos.

I witnessed a northern shrike twice now, catch and kill a shrew around the bird feeders.  Yesterday's  scenario was particularly interesting.  The shrike was perched on a small branch about 2 feet above the ground in an undisturbed area of snow.  The bird would be sitting casually but then look down on the ground in a specific area like he was ready to plunge head first into the snow.  He made this notion about 3 times before finally plunging down in the snow at about a 45 degree angle and pulling out the shrew.  The bird clearly could hear the shrew under the snow and was able to pinpoint it's location. I always thought shrikes hunted strictly by sight, but apparently they are also able to locate prey by sound underneath the snow as well.  The attack was vicious indeed, the bird repeatedly striking the shrew in the head and face and then finally administering the fatal bite to the back of the neck.  The pictures below are of another shrew it pulled off my rock landscaped wall and brought it underneath the bird feeders in an open area to kill it.

Continuing immature shrike reported yesterday in the hedgerow of a large farm field on the corner of Varga and Wormwood Hill Rd.  The farm is adjacent to Leander Pond and across the street from Knowlton Pond.  Brownish barring on breast, black mask clearly visible but not bold, hooked bill.  In typical behavior of shrikes, it appears to be stalking tree sparrows and house finches, and had a meal of something while we watched it.  It then flew up to perch at the top of a tall sapling which overlooks the hedgerow directly in front of us allowing for awesome looks and a photo op.

Rare; found yesterday evening by Dan Small; first seen fairly distantly, but bird was very active, and eventually worked it's way to within a few yards of the main through road (Ben's Point Rd); large-ish, neatly proportioned shrike; even in distant views, pinkish-brown cast to the mantle and crown was highly apparent, as was the long bill--which appeared sturdy, but not nearly so heavy as LOSH; at this distance, the head also looked relatively long and rectabgular, not beefy and bull-necked as in LOSH; in closer views, fine, extensive verminculations on throat, breast, and flanks were obvious, as was the pattern of the mask., which narrow and long, without black arching up over the bill--from most angles the lores even looked pale; bird sang intermittently, an almost GRCA-like song, but with individual parts much more widely spaced, and with clearer notes, some highly musical and others deeper and rattling; hunted actively during much of time observing it--it caught a cricket, and went after a MYWA and a RCKI (unsuccessfully); photos attached

This bird had the narrow mask of the Northern as compared to a Loggerhead, this bird had a thin line of white above and  along the length of the mask that also differentiated this bird from Loggerhead (I'm not sure this is as visible in the photos as it was in person), and this bird had a more strongly hooked bill than Loggerhead's short stubbier bill.  Those were the standout features for us, besides one other little detail that we noticed, which was a little bit of a white eye-arc under the eye that is also a Northern characteristic, not a Loggerhead's.

*Very rare in Cape May Co.; found a few minutes earlier by Alan Crawford. Paler backed and smaller headed than LOSH. Relatively narrow mask with eye bulging up; faint grayish in front of eye, and whitish over base of bill. Bill relatively long with obvious bale base to lower mandible, and strong hook at tip. Faint grayish barring/vermiculations on buff-white underparts. White rump. Perched on both high treetops and low shrubs, and went to ground several times, picking up insects (maybe crickets). Several aggressive encounters with Mockingbirds.

Thin dark mask and on bill, a noticeable pale spot at base of lower mandible, overall color is lighter gray than on a Loggerhead Shrike, note the white over the eye and base of bill instead of the black of the mask, as in Loggerhead shrike. Some beige mottling is seen on white breast. We didn't see the narrow lines on the breast but we didn't want to disturb her so kept our distance and only stayed a moment to take photos and took off. Gret came at little later and saw her bird again too.

NSHR visual 1 adult by plumage  KEY features to ID NSHR vs. LOSH:  light lower mandible patch at base bill; narrow band of white feathers across upper mandible; lighter gray upperpart feathers; perched body shape is more elongated rather than butterball-shaped as in LOSH  Stewart Fletcher, Photographer

Sevenmile Creek--Prickly Pear Land Trust (restricted access)
Observation Details: First observation at 0933. 1 counted on property. 1 individual(s) singing. Adult. First seen at the very beginning of the survey, perched on a metal fencepost SW of the start point. Later seen perched in the Acer negundo N of the stream in reach 4, then flying upstream to another perch after dropping down in the grasses. Next seen perched in the Prunus virginiana row in the SE part of reach 3, where it sang for several minutes. Seemed to imitate several species, including BBMA. Ca 1045 in reach 3, the shrike suddenly appeared and flew in aerial pursuit of 1 ATSP for ca 150 m E along the stream; it had apparently been unsuccessful when last seen perched near there in a dead Alnus incana over a pond. Later, NSHR seen in reach 1, hunting and perching in chokecherry thickets N of the stream. Detections (number 15-minute intervals in which the species was detected): 4 on property.

Exciting end of day to the Meaford CBC.

Locality: Hoback and Beattie St Area Neighborhoods
Observation Details: Hatch-year bird first seen at 1141 perched in the top of a leafless Prunus virginiana clump within 30 m of a house, on the NW flank of Sugarloaf Hill, with sloping grassland on 2 sides and residential houses interspersed with trees and gardens on the other sides. Brownish with faint mask and distinct barring underneath and a small pale patch at the base of the primaries. At the time I thought the appearance differed from the bird seen on 29 Oct about 500 m SSW, but comparison of photos reveals a very similar aspect. Thus, it seems quite likely that this is the same individual. Observed from 10 to 15 meters away until 1146, when it flew relatively directly about 40 m to the top of a cottonwood, also at the neighborhood edge. It remained there 1 or 2 minutes, then flew ca NW. Flight was direct and surprisingly (to me) fast with quick series of wingbeats punctuated by notable, short pauses; little undulation in flight. Not seen again during the rest of the count.

Fortuitous discovery from my front yard. While walking to my truck, I noticed a passerine-sized bird perched in the distant side of a neighborhood wood-lot in the very top of some mature deciduous trees (ash, etc) perhaps two hundred yards (or more) distant. The late afternoon light was fairly intense and highlighted the bird's apparent warm coloration, which, in combination with its size, shape and posture, and setting, was cause for excitement.   Dashing for the first optics available, I grabbed my daughter's 7x32 Eagle Optic binoculars and immediately identified the subject as a brown shrike; NOT a Brown Shrike, L.cristatus (though it's at the top of my dream-list for the region) but almost certainly a hatch-year Northern Shrike.   Nevertheless, with such an odd context and a still incomplete view pending (lacking any real detail, because of the above circumstances) the long-shot possibility is always worth the thrill.   Fortunately, the subject loitered long-enough for me to set-up my scope, confirm the identification and phone-scope some quick images. The images display a beautiful view of the bold "spotted" undertail pattern and warm brown scalloping on the chest and belly, both definitive for NSHR. So, some day. . . maybe. . . a Brown Shrike in New England, but, for now, another juvenile Northern Shrike, but this one a serendipitous yard-bird in a wooded residential neighborhood.

Caesar Creek SP--Observation Tower and Trail
Observation Details: Just after finding a Northern Mockingbird along Clarksville Rd., we found an adult Northern Shrike at the Caesar Creek Wildlife Area at 1640 (about 30 minutes before sunset.)  It was perched on the shrubs along the east side of the road (Old Clarksville Rd.) 0.1 miles from the intersection marked "Hopewell Day Lodge / Group Camping Area" straight ahead and "Wildlife Viewing Area" to the right, about halfway between that intersection and the first parking lot for the Observation Tower.  We were able to watch it for a few minutes until a car came along, honked at us, and the bird flew down and away.  We searched for the next 45 minutes until dark, but did not find it again.  Maybe it went to roost?  We managed some photos that clearly show the very hooked bill, the white above the bill, and that the narrow black mask doesn't extend above the eye.  In addition, the forehead color is light gray, as well as the back.  Fortunately, it cooperated for a series of photos, - some of the best are attached.  Directions:  Take SR73 east from Waynesville to Warren County Rd 37 (Clarksville Rd.)  then turn right.  Go 1.4 miles and turn left onto Middletown Rd. at the sign which says "Caesar Creek Lake Visitor Center" straight ahead and "Hopewell Recreation Area" to the left.  Go 0.2 miles, then right at the intersection and sign referenced above.  While we found the shrike along the main road leading to the observation tower trails, if it isn't found right away, try going to the observation tower.  You can see the entire area from the top of the tower, except for the area between the main road and Clarksville Rd.

This bird was slightly smaller than an American Robin that was perched on an adjacent post, but its shape was typical of a shrike.  It had a relatively stout bill that tapered from a heavy base to a tip that was blunt, if not slightly hooked, and which would have extended backward on the face to a point about halfway between the eye and the rear edge of the auriculars.  The forehead was relatively steep, and the crown was strongly rounded with a peak that was above and maybe a little behind the eye.  Typical of a shrike, this bird had a proportionately large head, a short and inconspicuous neck, and a plump and full-chested body with a posture that was closer to horizontal than diagonal.  The medium-length wings were typically held over the back, but at least once this bird lowered them enough for me to see the rump.  I thought the primary projection was between one-third and one-half the length of the exposed secondaries, and the wingtips appeared to reach right about to the tips of the uppertail coverts.  The tail was at least as long as the body, but it may have been as long as the body and head combined.  When held closed, the tail was parallel-sided, but when spread slightly the outer feathers appeared to be somewhat shorter than the central pair, resulting in the tail having a broadly rounded tip.  The legs and feet were unremarkable in their length and mass. This bird’s plumage patterns were typical of a North American shrike given a dark mask, grayish upperparts, mostly black wings and tail, and pale underparts.  I further noted that the forehead, crown, nape, back, and scapulars were medium-gray with a distinct brownish cast.  Demarcating the lower edge of the gray crown was a narrow and relatively indistinct supercilium that extended through the supraloral region to meet an eyering of the same color.  Also apparent was a well-defined band of buff across the immediate forehead that narrowly separated the bill from the gray crown.  The lores were relatively pale, yet I think they were darker than the supraloral region and the eyering.  The blackish “mask” was narrow and largely restricted to the auriculars, across which it extended behind the eye with the upper edge representing a sharp line that continued backward along the upper edge of the auriculars to a rounded terminus along their rear edge, and the lower edge extending from just below the eye back along the lower edge of the auriculars.  The pale color of the throat therefore extended up to the loral region and the lower edge of the auriculars.  The throat, breast, sides, and flanks generally appeared to be light gray with a somewhat uneven appearance; however, close inspection revealed narrow, dusky barring across at least the breast and sides. Returning to the upperparts, the back and scapulars were about the same shade of medium-gray and with the same brownish cast as the cap.  Narrowly separating the gray back from the black wings was a whitish crescent along the lower edge of the scapulars that appeared to be slightly broader rearward, where it curved around the inner part of the closed wing.  Although I noted little if any white in the remiges on this bird, there was a relatively strong contrast between the medium-brown remiges and what appeared to be jet-black greater-coverts.  A contrast on the median coverts between blackish centers and pale fringes created a scaly pattern near the shoulder that I missed in the field.  I noted just enough pale fringing on the tips of the exposed primaries to distinguish the various feathers in the wingtip.  The rump appeared to be creamy-white with a brownish cast centrally.  The upperside of the tail appeared to be dusky as opposed to uniformly black, and when spread, it had white edges across the distal third or so that were broader at the corners than internally. The bill was mostly black with a paler base, and the eyes were dark, but the legs and what I could see of the feet appeared to be blackish.

**Rare, a complete surprise. Flew right past Ant and I and perched on a tree south of the trail just west of the bathrooms. Super crisp adult with a bold facial mask and dark contrasting black and white on the wings, lending itself to a brief misidentification of loggerhead shrike, but the facial mask was sufficiently narrow for a quick revision. Subsequently seen with Isaac Grant and company, who were nearby when Ant and I sent out the alert. Quite active, flying back and forth from tree to tree and landing on a methane vent before strongly flying east and dropping into vegetation and out of view. Originally encountered here (40.5872274, -74.1858331); last seen dropping down low somewhere around the crossroad and locked gate here (40.5875334, -74.1846070)

First spotted adult in Hedgerow area between main park and large East field. Took some pictures and watched bird work it's way to far Northeast corner of this field. Sometimes perched on a shrub, sometimes hovered over something of interest. Clearly works a very large area. I left area to bird other areas and came back in about 40 minutes. Noticed shrike still to NE. 2 Bluejays were making very weird sounds - including a quasi peregrine sound in the hedgerow area so I went to check this out and all of a sudden shrike was back. I figured I had not seen it come back behind me. I took more pictures. When I got home, I realized I had two different birds: One Immature and one adult. The Immature was browner in tone, incomplete mask, lighter base of bill and slightly brown barring on chest. Adult was stark white and gray with solid black mask. (I did not see them at same time as didn't consider 2 until home looking at pics.)

Medium sized passerine - light gray above with lighter underside, black wings and mask, hooked bill.  Photos.  This was a cool sighting.  After spotting the shrike out in a distant tree, I sat down and watched it for awhile and eventually was rewarded to see it fly to a tree near me, then dive to the ground and come up with a mouse/small rodent.  It clung to the unfortunate victim with one, then both feet, much like a raptor with its prey - then flew with it deep into the branches of another tree further from me where it tore into the rodent, eating it immediately, and not caching it.

Observation Details: Scott Graber and I were walking along the road in the Deli Fields when a Bird flew through the bushes along the road. Immediately noting the pale color we both said "Mockingbird". I took a few steps beyond the tree it flew into and shouted "Shrike"! We both got on the bird and after taking several photos I posted the bird to our local text group. Eventually, Scotty Baldinger and Patrick Dechon joined us. The bird moved between a couple of treetops and eventually flew down into the dense underbrush. I noted I had seen amole/mouse working the leaf litter under there just a short time before. Eventually, about 15 minutes later the bird flew up into a tree. It cleaned its bill several times on a branch indicating to me it had eaten something. Eventually, after about an hour and just before dark, we left the bird perched in the tree. Hopefully it will continue tomorrow.

It was a very quiet Grey Cup celebration here, but I did some cleaning downstairs anyway! ;)  While earning those "brownie" points in anticipation of next week's CBCs, Sandra yelled “Get up here - what’s this bird??!!”  I quickly made it upstairs in time to see THIS bad boy sitting on the pergola.   While apparently the NSHR had no success trying to grab an afternoon snack, it was still VERY cool to see this species perched on our pergola from only a few metres away.   I’m guessing this is the possibly the same first-year bird that was here back on Nov. 1.  I managed a few snaps  with our little Canon SX720 HS before it flew off to the west.

Missed this bird yesterday. Heading west from Table Mt. Road, about 75M past the large palm tree I viewed what I thought may be a shrike fly across the road and drop into one of the two trees to my left. The bird was a shrike. I immediately noted a black mask that was thinner than that of a Loggerhead, and a bill that was a little larger and a hooked-pointed, than that of a Loggerhead. Scaling apparent on throat and belly. The bird flew across the road to the north as a vehicle passed by. I was able to obtain photos.

Another quick visit from the shrike, and sorry for the blurred picture. He is quick and does not hang around. The more interesting picture, though, is of the dead chickadee I found stashed in the top of a sapling, jammed into a Y branch, hanging by the neck. Though I did not see the shrike put him there, I am positive it is his work because of the proximity to my house and feeders, because of the way I have observed the shrike pursuing the chickadees, and because I know shrikes stash their food.

Observation Details: Continuing. Lifer. The third sighting of the day was the charm. He was stalking/hunting the northern edge of soybean field. Spotted him twice perched at tops of deciduous trees, but he flew off before I could get close enough for a positive ID and better than highly pixilated or just silhouette photos. Both times he flew noticed lots of wing flashing that reminded me of a mocking bird, but the silhouette was blockier compared to a mockingbirds sleek silhouette, After he flew down after the second sighting I didn't see him for a long while. Was about to give up when I  noticed he was perched at top of spruce tree. Got close enough to get a good look to ID and better quality photos.

Locality: Grand Forks County east of Hwy 18
Observation Details: Thanks to a reviewer's comments I have changed the ID from a Loggerhead in my earlier report. In a normal spring the expected shrike by now would be Loggerhead, although there have been recent reports of Northerns. I was partly influenced by that and also the bill seemed small with a smaller hook than is seen in Northerns. But I consulted five guides: Sibley, National Geographic, Peterson, Stokes and Floyd. These guides rather consistently show that for Loggerhead the black of the mask should definitely go above the eye, and the area immediately over the top of the bill should be black. In the photos here, the area above the bill is whitish and the black of the mask does not encompass the top of the eye. There is also the matter of the darkness of the gray in the back and its contrast with the black of the wings and tail. Judging that in the field or in photos is tricky because of lighting.

A continuing First Winter (immature) Northern Shrike was observed and photographed.  The bird had grayish-brown upper parts, flanks and cheeks and a gray finely barred breast and belly. The wings of the bird were dark with white patches. The bird had a thin dark mask behind its eye.  The mask did not extend in front of the eye and across the top of the bill, as is the case with a Loggerhead Shrike. The bill of the bird was robust and hooked.  The eyes and legs of the bird were dark. The undertail coverts of the bird were pale gray and the tail was black with white edges. The bird was observed and photographed near 30.681359, -97,361633 on a utility line just south of the lake near some covered picnic tables.

Locality: Rancho Tehama Road, ca. ¼ km W of Paskenta Road
Observation Details: This was a well-marked bird, yet it lacked bright coloration.  The face pattern was somewhat more complex but also weaker than that of a Loggerhead Shrike.  The mask was conspicuously narrow and essentially restricted to an elongate region of dull, blackish that extended from just behind the eye across the auriculars, though there was at least some darker coloration extending under the eye and into the lores.  Contrasting with the dark mask was the rich buff-forehead that connected with a buffy supraloral stripe and complete eyering.  I noted no blackish coloration in front of or above the eye, so the upper edge of the mask extended from the eyering back along the upper edge of the auriculars before curving around their rear terminus and then continuing back forward along the lower edge of the auriculars and less conspicuously the moustachial region.  The crown, nape, and back and sides of the neck were uniformly medium-brown with a gray cast, with the brown of the sides of the neck curving around to demarcate the rear terminus of the auriculars and then extend down to the sides of the breast.  The back and scapulars were similarly colored, but with the distal scapulars having a relatively narrow and diffuse crescent of pale-buff.  The closed wings appeared to be entirely dull black apart from narrow tips of white to the secondaries just above the slightly lighter and more brownish wingtip.  In fact, I had a hard time distinguishing the coverts and remiges in the closed wing.  It was only when the bird spread its wing to preen that I noted a narrow band of creamy-buff along the bases of primaries that appeared uniformly paler and more brownish than the rest of the wing.  The upper part of the rump was the same color as the back, but the grayish-brown blended to creamy-buff on the lower rump and possibly also the uppertail coverts.  The upperside of the closed tail was blackish much like the wings, but when the tail was spread I noted a whitish margin even when seen from above.  When seen from below, the outer rectrices were extensively white, at least along their outer edges, but when the bird spread its tail I noted that the white curved around the outer edges distally, though I did not think it reached the central feathers.  Contrasting with the darker upperparts, the underparts were generally light gray, though with the malar and submoustachial regions buffy, and a brownish wash to the sides of the breast and the rear flanks.  Also apparent across the breast, sides, belly, and flanks was dusky barring that was relatively narrow, well-defined, and with a wavy appearance.  The undertail coverts were more purely whitish and apparently unmarked, but I am less sure about both the color and pattern on the throat.  The bill was generally blackish but with the basal half or so of the lower mandible either pinkish or fleshy.  The eyes were dark, but I was unable to see any color.  What I was able to see of the legs and feet was black.

It appears that the shrike killed a pigeon and was then attacked by the chickens. By the time I got there, it had a broken leg and two badly injured wings. Given the condition of the roads, all we could do was put it in a warm greenhouse. I tried to offer it fresh pork, which it refused. It managed to somehow catch and kill a vole, but died several hours later.

Observation Details: 12:52 to 13:13 -  1st heard (buzzy, harsh breezeek note followed by a pause and repeated 2 more times); locate/visual 1 immature BROWN 1st WINTER (see The Sibley Guide to Birds, pg 341) NSHR (ID species in part by its pinkish base of lower mandible) perched in top of hardwood tree and remaining in place for a lengthy time --- usual shrike behavior is actively foraging.  BEHAVIOR:  Stays put (unlike a shrike that is a very active forager) on perch - turns out it is in wait mode.  Opens mouth wide 4xs - notice an enlargement in its CROP (photograph 2) after ~3rd open-mouth series, which pushes two pellets into crop from digestive tract; next TWO pellets are disgorged/discharged from mouth to the ground one-after-the-other - 1st pellet is small (documented by a lesser quality photo and also witnessed with binoculars) and 2nd pellet is large (photographs 3 and 4).  Stewart Fletcher, Photographer

Interesting behaviour. The Shrike was perched at the top of a 6 m pine tree in a field when the three crows approached, started calling and flew overhead. As soon as it heard their calls, the Shrike dove down and flew low across the field and headed straight into the dense shrubs at the edge of the field. It waited there until they passed before resuming a high perch.

Locality: Buena Vista Grasslands/Marsh--Co. W and Meyers Ln.

Observation Details: Continuing shrike found by Todd Ramsden. Showed up in middle of previously reported open area around 0958 after not being detected during my first walk around the perimeter of the area, then stayed in view for approximately the next hour before disappearing again. Initially seen perched on top of a tree here (39.9025164, -122.0727698), then flew to a couple trees nearby during my visit.   Large shrike - seemed larger than LOSH, though hard to judge without side-by-side comparison; substantial dark bill with pronounced hook to upper mandible, paler towards base; white over top of base of bill; weaker black mask than LOSH - more prominent behind the eye (a little bit wider than one eye width and about as long as two eye widths) than in front of it, and with white completely surrounding the eye, almost like spectacles; black eye; gray from crown to rump; rump whitish; upper tail black; whitish/very pale underparts with warm wash and fine barring from breast to belly that appeared maroon or brownish in my scope; black wings with small white wing patch and white tips to (secondaries/tertials?) and very thin pale tips to primaries; whitish utcs; black legs; underside of tail appeared mostly white due to white (tail spots?), though I never saw the tail spread well. [Notes taken before looking at my photos or field guide.]  After spending some time perched at the top of a tree, the shrike laddered down through the branches and then dove down into some nearby low bushes. It quickly maneuvered through them before flying back up to the tree holding what appeared to be a very downy and gray bird chick in its bill. After impaling the presumed chick on one of the branches, it proceeded to rip it up and eat the whole thing. Shortly after this, it started vocalizing spontaneously for the first time during my observation. I believe I heard and recorded at least three different types of vocalizations, which was extremely cool. It then spent the remainder of my observation generally preening, cleaning its bill against branches and surveying its realm before making a short flight and then disappearing.  All in all, I'm not sure if I've had a more prolonged and satisfying experience with a single bird in California since I started birding. Stoked the gamble of driving all the way up here for this bird paid off.  Photos. Audio. Video.

From the road at 37°54′38″ N  89°53′2″ W looking N along a row of grasses and short trees lining a ditch and separating two fields.  First view of gray speck at 12 o’clock in a tree at a range of about 125 yards, closing as the bird flew along the line closer to the road and me.   Bold enough black behind eye but tapering thru the eye to almost no mask between eye and bill exposing top of eye; narrow white border above mask, creating a white arc above eye and extending across forehead and top of bill; stout bill, pale at the base of the lower mandible, with prominent hook; fine gray barring-scaling on underparts, visible in photos.  Bird flew closer, stopped at the road, now 50 yards away, then eventually flew across the road in front of me to the S and disappeared in the heavily wooded section of the ditch S of the road.  At its closest bird presented a large, long-tailed profile.

Locality: Pahranagat NWR--Trees Below Upper Lake Dam
Observation Details: When first found, it was at a distance.  Though it had the basic look of a shrike, it was also clearly different.  The head was just a bit smaller and rounder in proportion to the body; the bird looked long - not as stocky as I think of a Loggerhead Shrikes as being; rather on the brown side of gray - not clear black, gray and white; it lacked a clear black mask.  The bill did not look especially long.  Thankfully it stayed put for a couple of photos, good enough for identification (attached).  In the photos, barring on the breast and the pale base of the lower mandible can be discerned.  A juvenile-plumaged bird.  The shrike was first perched near the top of some sunflower stalks.  It then flew to a two-foot tall stem along the road where we were walking, then continued into the sunflower/dogbane meadow not to be found again.  There were plenty of sparrows present - potential prey.  It was silent.

Rare and irregular visitor to Chester Co. and southeast Pennsylvania. This is most likely the same immature found on 2/25/17 by John Daniel. Despite efforts by birders, the bird eluded detection until 3/16/17. Since then, it has been seen by many. Description: large shrike, dark gray above with black wings containing white patches and a black tail. Underparts lighter gray with obvious fine horizontal barring. Face with faint black mask most prominent behind the eyes. Bill light silvery-brown with a definite hook at the tip. Initially as I approached the area, other birders were viewing the bird as it was perched deep within a bush. Over time, it worked it's way to the outer edge and then flew off landing atop a tall tree about 75 yds. away. It remained in that area for about five minutes and then flew off. The bird vocalized a lot. Audio files can be heard at http://ebird.org/ebird/pa/view/checklist/S35232824 by Barry Blust and http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S35229793 by Mike Gardner.

Locality: Creve Coeur Lake Memorial Park--Little Creve Coeur
Observation Details: From 38°42′37″ N  90°30′39″ W on the trail.  Bird flew into my FOV from the N and stopped to perch right in front of me, up in a tree, at a range of about 25 yards in excellent light.  My very first thought with eyes-only was cuckoo but, no, it was clearly a shrike with narrow mask, not covering the eye, and stout, not stubby, distinctly hooked bill—all well seen in the bins.  Also, largeish-looking; white on the forehead above the bill; dingy throat; variable amounts of white all around the eye forming a complete eyering; extensively barred underparts; small white patch at base of primaries really just a combination of white streaks.  Bird quickly flew away to the S.

Media notes: Pale bases of mandibles, tomial notch and tooth on upper mandible.
Observation Details: Reported at this location by Greg Gray yesterday evening. Robust shrike with a gray back demarcated from black primaries by a narrow white band. Narrow black mask mostly below and behind the eye; white supercilium extends in front of the eye.white lateral rectrices noted. The bill is black with pink base of both mandibles; a pronounced hook is seen on the upper mandible, with a tomial notch and tooth behind it. Fine gray vermiculations are present on dingy white breast in some views. Brutal lighting at this time of day makes comparison of different images necessary to see these details.

I assume this is the same individual that was first reported  by Hommert and Dean on Jan 15, 2020 at Bradford. It has been reported by about 5 additional birders on 15 Jan, then by Freibohle on 20 Jan, Decker and Pelc on 27 Jan, Bieksza on Jan 29, Johnson again on 10 March and myself on 17 March. This bird has been eluding many observers but it is still present. One NSHR lingered into late April, so stop by the dump pile in the early to mid-morning and give it a chance to show up. This bird is larger than a Loggerhead Shrike, narrower black mask, long heavy beak with a distinct hook at end of bill. The base of the lower mandible has a white patch. This is an adult bird with no brown of the immature shrike and has a strongly gray wavy thin lines on a lighter gray underside.The upper-parts are paler compared to the medium blue-gray upper-parts of a Loggerhead Shrike. This individual slowly bobbed its tail as I watched it perched on the top weeds above the dump pile.There is a white crescent over the eye and noticeably white over the bill. There is a slight hint of an eye ring at the lower edge of the eye.

I found what appears to be an immature Northern Shrike perched high atop a large cottonwood tree along the NE perimeter of the public access area, near the parking lot.  Both Sam Hough and I were able to get photos of the bird.  After reviewing the photos at home and consulting a number of books, I am convinced this is an immature Northern Shrike rather than an immature Loggerhead Shrike.  Characteristics that support this conclusion are:  * At this time of the year, an immature Loggerhead Shrike should have fairly close to adult plumage; this bird has retained some of its juvenile characteristics, and the plumage is quite different than that of an adult.  * Brown head with narrow mask that does not extend above the middle of the eyes; mask thinner in front of the eyes; white eye ring fairly easily seen.  * Bill not as long as what you would see in an adult; extensive pale area at base of lower mandible.  * Back has no barring and has a light brown tint.  * Very obvious light brown tint scaling on breast, belly and flanks (not barring like a juvenile Loggerhead Shrike).

Photos by Debby Parker through scope. OBSERVERS: Day one, Debby and Jim Parker and maybe Debbie House later. The next day Steve Brad and Tom Heindel saw it in the morning. Then on Friday, Bill Mitchel and Susan and Bob Steele had it. It was photographed by Steve Brad on Sunday, so it stayed for 6 days at least. HABITAT: Grazed grasslands with native vegetation and trees mostly along the river. The area had been burned in the past as many of the native Cottonwoods were blackened and pruned by fire. The river is bordered by cattails. There are at least three small pools formed by artesian wells but the cows use them for drinking so it’s messy. But in general the area is used for breeding by native birds later in the year. SHAPE AND SIZE: Shrike shaped but maybe longer looking, not so compact. Longish bill with obvious hook at the tip of upper mandible. The mask on the face was more narrow than on a Loggerhead Shrike (LOSH) and did not go over the round dark eye. The tail seemed long.  BEHAVIOR: Jim commented that when not using binoculars, it looked ghostly as it flew from one perch to another. It was difficult to relocate as it blended in and was similar in color to the silvery cottonwoods. At one point it went to the sandy-ground in between sage brush on a hillside nearby and must have been looking for food. It mostly stayed medium height and a few times lost itself in the highest limbs of a budding cottonwood, making it difficult to refind. We would refind it when it moved Documented for NAB

I saw a Shrike in a dead snag in the reclaimed area where raptors and the Shrike (when they are here) often sit.    After I took some photos and looked at them on my camera I discovered that an American Kestrel had replaced the Shrike on top of the snag.  That set off a round of furious calling by the Shrike as it repeatedly dove on the Kestrel.  In the middle of this a second Shrike showed up and joined the fray, although it was not clear which side it was on.  Later I saw a Shrike on the other side of the river, which I am assuming was one of the two previously seen.
