Locality: Sevenmile Creek--Prickly Pear Land Trust (restricted access)
Observation Details: LOTS of shrike sightings during the survey! All of adults, unlike the SY bird seen last week. Presumably all the same individual - but who knows? Seen in quite the range of locations along the creek and near the sewage lagoon; specific sightings all noted below. First seen at 0937, when it flew low over the stream corridor in the E end of reach 4 from somewhere upstream and landed in an alder ca 200 m downstream of the boundary fence, at the S edge of the riparian shrub zone. Remained until 0940; I did not see it depart. At 1007, reappeared just E of reach 4 and perched for less than 1 minute in an isolated, mostly-dead Chokecherry S of the creek, then it flew to an alder along the creek. At 1009 it flew upstream, low, and I lost sight of it somewhere in reach 4 - it had flown when a BBMA was in flight in the vicinity. I was not positive but did suspect that the magpie was perhaps chasing it away. A magpie (the same?) then perched in the alder where the shrike had been (photos of both magpie and shrike here). I spotted the shrike again near the E end of reach 4 from 1039 to 1046, apparently actively hunting, frequently changing perches. During this time it remained in an area within 100 m of the point where the E boundary intersects the stream. It perched near the top of living shrubs 4 times, dead shrubs 3 times, on a wire tree cage once, on or near a lump on the ground once, and at 3 different spots in a small area on the barbed wire fence. I last saw it perched along the stream ca 100 m upstream of me. Seen again at 1057 in the same E part of reach 4, perching in the tops of alders along the stream. I first detected it this time by movement low near some alders upstream of me. Apparently still hunting. Seemed fearless and flew to a perch ca 20 m from me, then another farther downstream. I wondered if it might actually be using my presence with the possibility that I might flush a rodent. No observations except frequent shrike sightings during the survey lent evidence for this hypothesis. At 1236, I saw the shrike perched in the alder snag just N of the diversion. At 1238, after defecating once and scratching its body briefly with its right foot it flew ca 100 m downstream and perched at the top of a live alder. It was still visible in the vicinity at 1247, perched in a shrub ca 200 m downstream of the diversion. Shrike again glimpsed briefly at 1318, ca 150 m above the rocky draw, perched and then dropping down (to the ground?) near low Chokecherries S of the stream. Saw it shortly after hearing SOSP "chimp" calls, which continued as I observed the shrike. Ca 1542, the shrike flew up from a dense willow area ca 50 m below the photo point and perched in a Russian-olive, then flew back down to the willow area and out of sight, ca 1 minute later. (just after the survey end, at 1607, I saw the shrike again, perched in a small Russian-olive ca 20 m E of the sewage lagoon fence, then flying ca 100 m SE to another Russian-olive).

I witnessed a northern shrike twice now, catch and kill a shrew around the bird feeders.  Yesterday's  scenario was particularly interesting.  The shrike was perched on a small branch about 2 feet above the ground in an undisturbed area of snow.  The bird would be sitting casually but then look down on the ground in a specific area like he was ready to plunge head first into the snow.  He made this notion about 3 times before finally plunging down in the snow at about a 45 degree angle and pulling out the shrew.  The bird clearly could hear the shrew under the snow and was able to pinpoint it's location. I always thought shrikes hunted strictly by sight, but apparently they are also able to locate prey by sound underneath the snow as well.  The attack was vicious indeed, the bird repeatedly striking the shrew in the head and face and then finally administering the fatal bite to the back of the neck.  The pictures below are of another shrew it pulled off my rock landscaped wall and brought it underneath the bird feeders in an open area to kill it.

Elaine Gosnell spotted NSHR land in snow out window. It flew from the snow carrying prey, landing on ground behind fence, then soon flew up into a Mountain Ash carrying the prey, landing about 2 m up in branches. In tree we identified prey as male House Finch. Ethan Gosnell took pictures and video; to be posted by Ethan. Flew off  to behind spruce within another minute or two. Exciting end of day to the Meaford CBC.

Locality: Hall Rd. X Monte Vista Ave.
Observation Details: This bird was found by Harold Reeve late on 10/14/2017. I arrived around 9 am, meeting Harold and Sherrie Reeve, Eric Caine, and Jim Gain at the site where the bird was initially seen on Hall Road. After about a half hour or so, Eric drove down to the clump of willows that intersected Monte Vista Road, finding the bird shortly thereafter. We all moved to that spot on Monte Vista, where I eventually saw the bird. At first it appeared perched on the willows, then dropped down to the fenceline, quickly flying to a perpendicular fenceline some distance away. To my eye, the bird appeared to have a lightly brownish cast, as if someone had put a dash of coffee into a cup of cream. Fine vermiculations were visible on the underparts. The mask was poorly developed. The bird appeared to have a large bill with distinct hook, and the mandible was light. A Loggerhead Shrike at this time of year should not show immature plumage features as I understand.
Facial plumage and bill coloration might indicate a 1st-winter bird.

Locality: Hoback and Beattie St Area Neighborhoods
Observation Details: Hatch-year bird first seen at 1141 perched in the top of a leafless Prunus virginiana clump within 30 m of a house, on the NW flank of Sugarloaf Hill, with sloping grassland on 2 sides and residential houses interspersed with trees and gardens on the other sides. Brownish with faint mask and distinct barring underneath and a small pale patch at the base of the primaries. At the time I thought the appearance differed from the bird seen on 29 Oct about 500 m SSW, but comparison of photos reveals a very similar aspect. Thus, it seems quite likely that this is the same individual. Observed from 10 to 15 meters away until 1146, when it flew relatively directly about 40 m to the top of a cottonwood, also at the neighborhood edge. It remained there 1 or 2 minutes, then flew ca NW. Flight was direct and surprisingly (to me) fast with quick series of wingbeats punctuated by notable, short pauses; little undulation in flight. Not seen again during the rest of the count.

Locality: Along RMA NWR auto tour route.
Observation Details: Photos are of the same bird - different sides of the road and sun. Perched atop plant stalks (Mullein?) and with mouth open virtually the entire whole time. "Northern" because of full eyering, black stripe not extending into lore, black stripe intersecting the eye below the top and not encompassing the eye, lacking white spot on primaries, and faint white lining above black stripe behind eye. Unfortunately I could not get it to face me for breast shots. The bill on the last photo gives me pause - it seems shorter like a Loggerhead vs long and narrow like Northern, but the other factors seem more compelling.

Media notes: This tiny [10"] bird was almost a grey colour as it hopped from log to log in the rain, watching our sparrow feeder. When the sun came out, it appeared almost creamy-coloured. Very beautiful.
Observation Details: VERY excited to see this bird fly in this afternoon!! He flew in over the feeding area where the Juncos and other sparrows were--fast as could be!! Many sparrows jumped down into the daisy foliage and we wondered why--THEN we knew!! Didn't take any--rather, landed on an Arbutus Limb. Then, it flew onto our curved sign log--then to two other logs, always watching the feeding area up by the house. This gave us lots of opportunity to view it--a beautiful bird for sure!! Colours changed with the lighting--it had been raining and it's colours were quite grey--the late afternoon sun popped out, low in the sky and it's appearance turned a creamy colour.

This bird had the narrow mask of the Northern as compared to a Loggerhead, this bird had a thin line of white above and  along the length of the mask that also differentiated this bird from Loggerhead (I'm not sure this is as visible in the photos as it was in person), and this bird had a more strongly hooked bill than Loggerhead's short stubbier bill.  Those were the standout features for us, besides one other little detail that we noticed, which was a little bit of a white eye-arc under the eye that is also a Northern characteristic, not a Loggerhead's.

(This sighting was subsequently accepted by VSO records committee ... original notes follow ) Continuing bird........ In my opinion this bird (NSHR) can be differentiated from Loggerhead Shrike by thinner black mask with a very visible white line above mask and above eye and across base of bill. Black mask was much thinner between eye and bill (lores). Mask hooked downward at nape. Bill was longer and more strongly hooked than one would expect for a Loggerhead. First third of lower mandible was a pale blond brown color. Upper mandible showed some pale areas as well near the base. This pale area covering the base of lower mandible is more typical of NSHR. Loggerheads typically have all black bills. Breast and belly showed prominent grayish barring with a strong brownish cast. Young Loggerheads can show barring on breast but not to this degree and if they have barring on breast then back is barred as well. This bird shows a smooth light gray color on back and crown. No contrast between gray of crown and gray back. In Loggerhead the crown would typically be darker. Furthermore most immature Loggerheads would not show barring at this time of year. This bird also distinguished itself from Loggerhead behaviorally by perching almost exclusively (at least during the times I observed the bird) at the top of tall deciduous trees dropping to the ground periodically to hunt. Almost always the bird would reappear at the top of yet another deciduous tree. The bird was also observed to pump its tail with fair frequency. Many photos taken but lighting and distance were problematic.
This immature bird bumped into the dining room window. It was a little dazed for a few minutes, but appeared to recover well.

Found by Debby Parker 28 Oct. Life bird and on our backyard birdfeeder!  A brown barred shrike with a noticeably long and hooked bill.  The blackish auricular patch was narrow, washed-out looking, and ill defined.  There was a slight white eyering, especially above the eye.  In some light the back color was almost white.  The wings always appeared solid black.  The base of the bill, especially the lower mandible, appeared bone colored, maybe pinkish.  The brown horizontal barring on the breast was discrete and fine but obvious. Continued through 30 Nov 2002.
